``` 
#version 330

in vec2 vTexCoord;
out vec4 fragColor;

uniform sampler2D tex;

void main()
{
    // Sample the texture at the given texture coordinate
    vec4 texel = texture(tex, vTexCoord);

    // Convert the color to grayscale using the luminance method
    float luminance = dot(texel.rgb, vec3(0.299, 0.587, 0.114));
    vec3 grayscale = vec3(luminance);

    // Output the grayscale color
    fragColor = vec4(grayscale, texel.a);
}
``` 
This shader takes a texture sampler as input, and applies a grayscale filter to the texture by converting each texel's RGB value to grayscale using the luminance method. The resulting grayscale value is then outputted as the RGB value for the fragment. The alpha value of the input texel is passed through unchanged and is used as the alpha value for the output fragment.

To create a frame-by-frame animation in React.js, you can use the <canvas> element and the requestAnimationFrame() function to render each frame. Here's an example of how you can do it:

Create a new React component that renders a <canvas> element:

    import React, { useRef, useEffect } from 'react';

    function Animation() {
      const canvasRef = useRef(null);

      useEffect(() => {
        const canvas = canvasRef.current;
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

        let frame = 0;

        function render() {
          // Clear the canvas
          ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

          // Draw the current frame
          // TODO: Draw your animation frame here

          // Increase the frame counter
          frame++;

          // Request the next frame
          requestAnimationFrame(render);
        }

        // Start the animation
        requestAnimationFrame(render);

        // Clean up when the component unmounts
        return () => cancelAnimationFrame(render);
      }, []);

      return (
        <canvas ref={canvasRef} width={640} height={480} />
      );
    }

    export default Animation;

1. Inside the render() function, you can draw each frame of your animation using the canvas drawing API. For example, you can draw an image or a shape, move it slightly, and then draw it again in the next frame.

2. Increase the frame counter at the end of each frame, so you can keep track of which frame you're currently rendering.

3. Use the requestAnimationFrame() function to request the next frame of the animation. This function will automatically call your render() function again as soon as the browser is ready to render the next frame.

4. Finally, return the <canvas> element from your component and set its ref attribute to canvasRef, so you can access the canvas context inside the useEffect() hook.

Once you have created your frame-by-frame animation component, you can import it into your page and render it like any other React component:

    import Animation from './Animation';

    function App() {
      return (
        <div>
          <Animation />
        </div>
      );
    }

    export default App;

